- tests/test_permission_middleware.py

## Registry → Teams sub-menu leaked to non-admins in the top navbar

User report: "Teams sub menu is available (in the navbar not the page)
for all". ``menu_config.json`` marks the ``teams`` item under
``registry-domains`` with ``"admin_only": true``. The sidebar template
(``_sidebar_nav.html``) already honours that flag — it adds the
``admin-only-nav`` class with inline ``display:none`` and the
``navbar.js#showAdminNavItems`` helper reveals it only for admins.

The top navbar branch in ``base.html`` for non-``domain`` menus (the
Registry / Digital Twin path, at ~line 124) rendered every item
identically — no ``admin_only`` handling — so the Teams dropdown item
was visible to viewers and editors. The Teams API (``/settings/teams``)
was already protected by ``PermissionMiddleware`` under
``_PERM_ADMIN_ONLY_PREFIXES = ("/settings",)``, so non-admins clicking
the item hit a 403 rather than a data leak, but the menu entry itself
was wrong.

Fix (``src/front/templates/base.html``): apply the same
``admin-only-nav`` class + inline ``display:none`` pattern that the
sidebar already uses, so ``showAdminNavItems()`` can reveal it for
admins and everyone else sees the ``display:none`` until then. The
domain-menu branch (line 98/101) keeps its own existing rendering —
no ``admin_only`` items currently live there.

